orig_caption:
The former German submarine UB 148 at sea, after having been surrendered to the Allies. UB-148, a small coastal submarine, was laid down during the winter of 1917 and 1918 at Bremen, Germany, but never commissioned in the Imperial German Navy. She was completing preparations for commissioning when the armistice of November 11 ended hostilities. On November 26, UB-148 was surrendered to the British at Harwich, England. Later, when the United States Navy expressed an interest in acquiring several former U-boats to use in conjunction with a Victory Bond drive, UB-148 was one of the six boats allocated for that purpose.

orig_caption: The most famous California road trip is back on. It stretches more than 650 miles and knits together all that encapsulates California in the American imagination: the Pacific Coast, the redwood forests, the automobile. For the first time in more than a year, California’s Highway 1 — often called the Pacific Coast Highway — is open without interruption, after a chunk of it was wiped away in a massive landslide last year. The first pieces of the highway opened in the 1920s. Later, the route became entwined with the lore of California. Over the years, and not infrequently, landslides have taken out portions of the highway. But none were as big as the one in May 2017, when some 6 million cubic yards of earth moved after torrential rainfalls, adding 15 acres of coastline. Before that, in 2016, a large wildfire near Big Sur burned more than 130,000 acres. Our staff photographer @jimwilson125 took this photo of fog along the coastline yesterday near #BigSur. | There is no shortage of travel literature about a road trip up or down the Pacific Coast Highway. Visit the link in our profile for some suggestions.

This week is the world premiere of William Kentridge’s major new work The Head & the Load in Tate Modern's #TurbineHall. Tate joined forces with @1418now, the UK’s arts programme for the #WWI centenary, to commemorate the significant contribution of African men and women in this conflict. Kentridge’s work tells the untold story of the hundreds of thousands of African porters and carriers who served in British, French and German forces.

Thank you to everyone involved in the making of The Head & the Load. The full performance will be available to watch online from 21 July, meanwhile watch today's stories for an extract of this special performance.

orig_caption:
Home to the Earls of Marischal, Dunnottar Castle has held host to William Wallace, Mary Queen of Scots, the Marquis of Montrose and the future King Charles II.
▫️
Most famously though, it was at Dunnottar Castle that a small garrison held out against the might of Cromwell’s army for eight months and saved the Scottish Crown Jewels from destruction.
▫️
After the war the heavily damaged Dunnottar was retained by the Army and used as a depot until returned to the Keith family in 1695. During this period the ruling Stuart dynasty had been overthrown and replaced with the dual Protestant monarchs of William of Orange and his wife Mary.
▫️
Although widely accepted, a Jacobite movement emerged and in 1707 William Keith, Ninth Earl Marischal was implicated and imprisoned. Although released his son - George Keith, Tenth Earl Marischal - later participated in the 1715 Jacobite rebellion including fighting at the Battle of Sherrifmuir. With the defeat of the uprising he fled abroad only returning in 1763 after a pardon granted specifically at the request of Frederick the Great of Prussia.
▫️
During this period Dunnottar had been sold into the hands of the York Building Company who plundered the ruined remains for masonry, lead and other items of value.
▫️
The impregnable fortress is perched on a giant conglomorate on the edge of the North-Sea.
▫️

caption: in king robert ii of scotland granted the barony of glamis to sir john lyon of forteviot four years later sir john married roberts daughter princess joanna it was their son sir john lyon of glamis who began work on turning the old royal hunting lodge he had inherited into the glamis castle you see today ▫ the lyons of glamis nearly came unstuck over an argument in the early s as a child james v was dominated and later kidnapped by his stepfather archibald douglas when james v gained power in he took his revenge on the whole of his stepfathers family ▫ archibald douglass sister janet douglas was the widow of john lyon th lord glamis james v brought charges of witchcraft against her had her imprisoned in edinburgh castle and then in had her burned at the stake infant son was also condemned to death relations with the crown were later restored when mary queen of scots stayed at glamis castle in ▫ john the th earl supported the jacobite uprising and was killed at the battle of sheriffmuir a month later and before fleeing the country as the uprising collapsed james viiiiii stayed at glamis castle with of his supporters while there he is said to have healed a number of locals by touching them a sign to the jacobites that he was indeed the rightful king ▫ in john the th earl of strathmore married mary eleanor bowes heiress to the vast estates of her father george bowes john and marys son the th earl took the family name of bowes lyon and established a new family crest ▫ more recently glamis castle served as the childhood home of elizabeth bowes lyon queen elizabeth the queen mother and was birthplace of her daughter princess margaret ▫ image by malteserosephotography
orig_caption:
In 1372 King Robert II of Scotland granted the Barony of Glamis to Sir John Lyon of Forteviot. Four years later Sir John married Robert's daughter, Princess Joanna. It was their son, Sir John Lyon of Glamis, who began work on turning the old royal hunting lodge he had inherited into the Glamis Castle you see today.
▫️
The Lyons of Glamis nearly came unstuck over an argument in the early 1500s. As a child, James V was dominated, and later kidnapped, by his stepfather, Archibald Douglas. When James V gained power in 1528 he took his revenge on the whole of his stepfather's family.
▫️
Archibald Douglas's sister, Janet Douglas, was the widow of John Lyon, 6th Lord Glamis. James V brought charges of witchcraft against her, had her imprisoned in Edinburgh Castle and then, in 1537 had her burned at the stake. Janet’s infant son was also condemned to death. Relations with the crown were later restored when Mary, Queen of Scots stayed at Glamis Castle in 1562.
▫️
John, the 5th Earl, supported the 1715 Jacobite uprising and was killed at the Battle of Sheriffmuir. A month later and before fleeing the country as the uprising collapsed, James VIII/III, stayed at Glamis Castle with 88 of his supporters. While there he is said to have healed a number of locals by touching them, a sign to the Jacobites that he was indeed the rightful king.
▫️
In 1767 John, the 9th Earl of Strathmore, married Mary Eleanor Bowes, heiress to the vast estates of her father, George Bowes. John and Mary's son, the 10th Earl, took the family name of Bowes Lyon and established a new family crest.
▫️
More recently, Glamis castle served as the childhood home of Elizabeth Bowes Lyon (Queen Elizabeth, The Queen Mother) and was birthplace of her daughter, Princess Margaret.
▫️

orig_caption: Photograph by @CristinaMittermeier // The government of the Democratic Republic of Congo remains steadfast in opening up parts of Virunga and Salonga National Parks, two UNESCO World Heritage Sites, for oil exploration and drilling. Virunga, Africa’s oldest national park, is one of the world’s most biologically diverse areas and is home to over half of the global population of critically endangered mountain gorillas. Similar in merit, Salonga protects several endemic endangered species and covers a significant part of the Congo Basin, the world’s second-largest rainforest after the Amazon. Allowing drilling in these parks produces nothing positive; large amounts of carbon dioxide will be released into the atmosphere; biodiversity in the area will be lost; endangered species will be put at significant risk; the livelihoods of thousands of traditional farmers and fishermen who rely on unpolluted lands and water will be in peril. #FollowMe at @CristinaMittermeier or more photography that helps mend the plight of our planet by sparking dialogues on conservation. #Wildlife #Endangered #Conservation #Gorilla #Oil #Nature

caption: kilchurn castle was built in the mid s by sir colin campbell st lord of glenorchy ▫ in colin second son of duncan campbell was granted glenorchy at the north end of loch awe this grant was designed to ensure loyalty following the sudden death of his elder brother gillespic ▫ descendants the campbells of glenorchy later earls of breadalbane were the most powerful of the numerous cadets of clan campbell indeed there were times when this branch almost rivalled the clan chiefs the earls of argyll for supremacy ▫ throughout its history the castle has served as a fortress comfortable residence and later a garrison stronghold and contains the oldest surviving barracks on the british mainland ▫ after the first jacobite rising of kilchurn was converted into a garrison stronghold but was abandoned by the end of the s ▫ image by ovunno
orig_caption:
Kilchurn Castle was built in the mid-1400s by Sir Colin Campbell, 1st Lord of Glenorchy.
▫️
In 1432, Colin, second son of Duncan Campbell, was granted Glenorchy, at the north end of Loch Awe. This grant was designed to ensure Colin’s loyalty following the sudden death of his elder brother, Gillespic.
▫️
Colin’s descendants, the Campbells of Glenorchy (later earls of Breadalbane), were the most powerful of the numerous cadets of Clan Campbell. Indeed, there were times when this branch almost rivalled the clan chiefs, the earls of Argyll, for supremacy.
▫️
Throughout its history, the castle has served as a fortress, comfortable residence and later a garrison stronghold, and contains the oldest surviving barracks on the British mainland.
▫️
After the first Jacobite Rising of 1689, Kilchurn was converted into a garrison stronghold, but was abandoned by the end of the 1700s.
▫️
Image by @ovunno ———————————————————

caption: propaganda was being used long before the outbreak of world war one but the use of posters rather than handbills was pioneered during the war almost from the outset the british government through the parliamentary recruiting committee set about producing posters to swell the ranks of britains small professional army with volunteers the first posters relied simply on text to get their message across as the war progressed the posters become increasingly sophisticated with artists using striking images to convey pro war messages although recruitment was the initial focus for posters they were also employed to promote patriotism justify the war raise money procure resources promote accepted standards of behaviour often these themes crossed over for instance with patriotic images being woven into efforts to recruit men and raise money comrades jonthecollector unitedwarfronts be sure to follow us for more facts about wwi
orig_caption:
Propaganda was being used long before the outbreak of World War One, but the use of posters, rather than handbills, was pioneered during the war. Almost from the outset, the British government, through the Parliamentary Recruiting Committee, set about producing posters to swell the ranks of Britain's small professional army with volunteers.

The first posters relied simply on text to get their message across; as the war progressed the posters become increasingly sophisticated with artists using striking images to convey pro-war messages. Although recruitment was the initial focus for posters, they were also employed to:

1) Promote patriotism
2) Justify the war
3) Raise money
4) Procure resources
5) Promote accepted standards of behaviour.

Often these themes crossed over, for instance with patriotic images being woven into efforts to recruit men and raise money. ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

orig_caption: A new generation of niche sports is looking to streaming instead of big networks to find more exposure and new fans. Consider arm wrestling. Steve Kaplan, president of the @walunderground, earnestly believes arm wrestling is the sport of the future. But it’s also a sport of the past. The World’s Strongest Man competition was a pillar of the so-called “trash sports” craze in the 1970s. Now, tech powerhouses like Amazon, Facebook and YouTube are experimenting with sports rights. “It is the greatest time to be a sports fan in the history of the world,” said Burke Magnus, the @espn executive in charge of programming. No matter how small or unpopular a league or team is, their games are probably streaming to fans somewhere, he said. To be sure, streaming services and the niche sports they show face plenty of significant challenges before they become a viable alternative to broadcast or cable TV. But Steve is an optimist. Arm wrestling was ready for a reboot, he says. “It’s ordinary people doing extraordinary things.” @mattrothphoto took this photo of Matt Mask, left, competing against Marcio Barboza at the World Armwrestling League. Visit the link in our profile to read more.

caption: gylen castle was built in the s as a stronghold of clan macdougall and a strategic centre of control and observation on the approach to oban ▫ the castle consisted of a four storey l plan tower house that was built in the scots baronial style defence was clearly foremost in the minds of the builders of gylen castle but this was not the only consideration the castle was intended to impress and to act as a clear status symbol for its owner accordingly craftsmen were employed to create the oriel window that still dominates the landward frontage as well as numerous romanesque style carvings ▫ the macdougalls still owned the castle upon the outbreak of the wars of three kingdoms in the mid seventeenth century the clan were supporters of the royalist cause and in a detachment of covenanters besieged the castle the duration of the siege is not known but it was long enough for the lack of water to become a significant problem for the garrison although a natural spring existed it was clearly insufficient ▫ ever mindful of the fearful massacre at dunaverty castle in may the clansmen within the castle surrendered this did not save them however and they were all massacred save john macdougall who was spared on the grounds he was just a child gylen was sacked and burnt ▫ gylen castle has remained a ruin ever since the covenanter attack the ruins became famous after being painted by the artist jwm turner in the structure was stabilised by the ministry of works in the s but it was under the auspices of morag macdougall that significant work was done on the structure aided by donations from historic scotland and the heritage lottery fund ▫ image by orsayoban
orig_caption:
Gylen Castle was built in the 1580s as a stronghold of Clan MacDougall and a strategic centre of control and observation on the approach to Oban.
▫️
The castle consisted of a four storey 'L' plan Tower House that was built in the Scots Baronial style. Defence was clearly foremost in the minds of the builders of Gylen Castle but this was not the only consideration. The castle was intended to impress and to act as a clear status symbol for its owner. Accordingly craftsmen were employed to create the Oriel window that still dominates the landward frontage as well as numerous Romanesque style carvings
▫️
The MacDougalls still owned the castle upon the outbreak of the Wars of Three Kingdoms in the mid-seventeenth century. The clan were supporters of the Royalist cause and in 1647 a detachment of Covenanters besieged the castle. The duration of the siege is not known but it was long enough for (the lack of) water to become a significant problem for the garrison. Although a natural spring existed it was clearly insufficient.
▫️
Ever mindful of the fearful massacre at Dunaverty Castle in May 1647, the clansmen within the castle surrendered. This did not save them however and they were all massacred, save John MacDougall who was spared on the grounds he was just a child. Gylen was sacked and burnt.
▫️
Gylen Castle has remained a ruin ever since the Covenanter attack. The ruins became famous after being painted by the artist J.W.M Turner in 1831. The structure was stabilised by the Ministry of Works in the 1950s but it was under the auspices of Morag MacDougall that significant work was done on the structure aided by donations from Historic Scotland and the Heritage Lottery Fund.
▫️

caption: eilean donan castle overlooks the isle of skye at the point where three great sea lochs meet ▫ bishop donan chose the tranquil spot back in ad to settle on and create a monastic cell the first castle was later established in the th century by alexander ii in an effort to help protect the area from viking incursions ▫ in the castle was involved in the jacobite uprising following which eilean donan lay in silent ruin for the best part of two hundred years ▫ the castle we see today was reconstructed as a family home between and by lt col john macrae gilstrap ▫ image by marcelsiebert
orig_caption:
Eilean Donan Castle overlooks the Isle of Skye, at the point where three great sea-lochs meet.
▫️
Bishop Donan chose the tranquil spot back in 634AD to settle on and create a monastic cell. The first castle was later established in the 13th century by Alexander II in an effort to help protect the area from Viking incursions.
▫️
In 1719 the castle was involved in the Jacobite uprising; following which Eilean Donan lay in silent ruin for the best part of two hundred years.
▫️
The castle we see today was reconstructed as a family home between 1912 and 1932 by Lt Col John MacRae-Gilstrap.
▫️

Hey everyone, this is my first post here so I hope I'm doing it right. The Pohangina River was a location I had in mind for a while to re-shoot, but struggled with the cloud cover in this area of the country. It's getting late in the season for shooting the Milky Way core rising but it was still low enough for this composition. Unfortunately my gumboots were slightly too short to keep the water out at some points while trying to wade through the river. ;(

orig_caption:
Tantallon Castle was built in the mid 14th century by William, Earl of Douglas.
▫️
On the death of William in 1384, he left a legitimate heir, James, and an illegitimate son, George. James inherited the entire Douglas estates but he was killed at the Battle of Otterburn. The mother of the illegitimate George now sought to promote her son's claim. The Douglas family divided into two factions with James' heir - Archibald the Grim - leading the Black Douglases whilst George headed the Red Douglases. Tantallon Castle was held by the latter.
▫️
George died in 1403 and was followed by his son, William. William was a loyal supporter of James II and was used by the King as a gaoler for key opponents. On Royal orders William incarcerated Alexander MacDonald, Lord of the Isles at Tantallon between 1429 and 1431. He later led the King's army at the Battle of Arkinholm (1455) where he decisively defeated the Black Douglases.
▫️
The family also frequently clashed with the Crown. It was besieged by both James IV and James V. The end came for Tantallon Castle in 1650. In September that year an English army under Oliver Cromwell had defeated the Scots at the Battle of Dunbar and had subsequently overrun southern Scotland. A force of 91 men under Alexander Seton established their base at Tantallon Castle. Operating from this secure facility they launched attacks on the English supply lines which followed the coastal route back towards Berwick-upon-Tweed.
▫️
Unsurprisingly the English were not willing to leave this garrison in their rear and General George Monck was tasked with reducing the castle. He commenced an artillery bombardment, smashing a breach and took the castle. The damage was so extensive the castle was never rebuilt.
▫️

Magical!✨🌈 Felipe Pantone, “Optichromie 101,” 2018, Spray paint and UV Ink on aluminum panel 47”x 47”. . 
Felipe Pantone’s Artifact to Artifact Communicator presents five paintings and one car debating about dynamism, transformation, and impermanence. Pantone is an Argentinian-Spanish artist who started doing graffiti at the age of 12 and graduated with a Fine Art degree in Valencia, Spain. Pantone’s body of work spans from graffiti to kinetic art. High-contrast colors, geometric patterns, and Op Art elements insinuate motion and challenge perspective in a mix of computer-generated graphics, conventional graffiti, typography, and abstraction. Pantone maintains his studio Spain but currently lives in New York. .

caption: castle stalker has a long and turbulent history originally built as a fort by the macdougalls in the early th century in the stewarts became the lords of lorn and were granted the land which included the castle for the next years the castle remained a stewart stronghold until it was lost to the campbells in a drunken bet ▫ the stewarts of appin regained the castle in when they came out with king james vii but after defeat at the battle of dunkeld the castle was again forfeited to the campbells the stewarts under ardsheal refused to hand it over when it was then besieged by the campbells for several months until ardsheal was granted an honourable surrender in ▫ at the time of the rising castle stalker was held by the campbells with a garrison of about government troops although the stewarts of appin were solidly behind prince charles and raised a regiment of the castle was too strong for them to take ▫ the last campbell was born in the castle in and campbells continued to reside in it until about when they built a new house on the mainland ▫ in about the roof either fell in or was perhaps removed to avoid roof tax and the castle was abandoned ▫ in the castle was regained from the campbells by charles stewart of achara who purchased it and carried out some basic preservation work to stem its decay ▫ in his successor duncan stewart who was governor of sarawak was murdered and the castle devolved on his widow ▫ in lt col d r stewart allward negotiated terms for the purchase of the castle and spent the next ten years rebuilding and restoring it as it is today ▫ image by bokehmn
orig_caption:
Castle Stalker has a long and turbulent history. Originally built as a fort by the MacDougalls in the early 14th century, in 1388 the Stewarts became the Lords of Lorn and were granted the land which included the castle. For the next 200 years the castle remained a Stewart stronghold, until it was lost to the Campbell's in a drunken bet.
▫️
The Stewarts of Appin regained the Castle in 1689 when they came out with King James VII but after defeat at the battle of Dunkeld the Castle was again forfeited to the Campbells. The Stewarts under Ardsheal refused to hand it over when it was then besieged by the Campbells for several months until Ardsheal was granted an honourable surrender in 1690.
▫️
At the time of the 1745 Rising, Castle Stalker was held by the Campbells with a Garrison of about 59 Government troops. Although the Stewarts of Appin were solidly behind Prince Charles, and raised a regiment of 300, the Castle was too strong for them to take.
▫️
The last Campbell was born in the Castle in 1775 and Campbells continued to reside in it until about 1800 when they built a new house on the mainland.
▫️
In about 1840 the roof either fell in or was perhaps removed to avoid roof-tax and the Castle was abandoned.
▫️
In 1908 the Castle was regained from the Campbells by Charles Stewart of Achara who purchased it and carried out some basic preservation work to stem its decay.
▫️
In 1947 his successor, Duncan Stewart, who was Governor of Sarawak, was murdered and the Castle devolved on his widow.
▫️
In 1965 Lt. Col. D. R. Stewart Allward negotiated terms for the purchase of the Castle and spent the next ten years rebuilding and restoring it as it is today.
▫️

caption: in attempting to fight through enemy trenches or to defend against attack all armies came to rely heavily on grenades these simple hand thrown weapons had been invented hundreds of years before but had not been widely used since the napoleonic era reinvented by the requirements of trench warfare the first grenades in were often hand made consisting of old cans filled with nails and bits of metal and packed with gunpowder they often proved as dangerous to their makers as to their intended targets due to the risk of premature explosion by the end of all armies were being supplied with hand bombs rifle grenadiers fired specifically modified grenades from rifles while the infantry on both sides carried dozens of different types the germans tended to prefer the stick bomb which could be thrown farther but had a smaller explosive charge the british and canadians used egg shaped hand grenades which could be thrown about metres metres fewer than the german sticks but carried a larger explosive charge by all infantry carried grenades all major assaults required attacking troops to carry extra grenades to capture their objectives and then hold them against enemy counterattack comrades jonthecollector unitedwarfronts be sure to follow us for more facts about wwi
orig_caption:
In attempting to fight through enemy trenches, or to defend against attack, all armies came to rely heavily on grenades. These simple, hand-thrown weapons had been invented hundreds of years before, but had not been widely used since the Napoleonic era. Reinvented by the requirements of trench warfare, the first grenades in 1914 were often hand-made, consisting of old cans filled with nails and bits of metal and packed with gunpowder. They often proved as dangerous to their makers as to their intended targets, due to the risk of premature explosion.

By the end of 1915, all armies were being supplied with hand bombs. Rifle grenadiers fired specifically modified grenades from rifles, while the infantry on both sides carried dozens of different types. The Germans tended to prefer the stick bomb, which could be thrown farther but had a smaller explosive charge. The British and Canadians used egg-shaped hand grenades, which could be thrown about 30 metres (10 metres fewer than the German sticks), but carried a larger explosive charge.

By 1917, all infantry carried grenades. All major assaults required attacking troops to carry extra grenades to capture their objectives and then hold them against enemy counterattack.

(via @facts)
In 1955, as many as 20,000 children a year were being permanently paralyzed by polio. When Salk made his breaktrough discovery (which all but eradicated the disease), he treated the innovation as his gift to humanity. When asked who owns the patent he remarked, "Well the people, I would say. There is no patent. Could you patent the sun?" This decision not to keep the patent for himself meant Salk gave up the ability to make as much as $7 billion. Do you think large pharmaceutical companies have a responsibility to the world? caption: stirling castle was first mentioned around and is considered as one of the most historically important sites in scotland ▫ throughout the wars of independence with england stirling was hotly fought over and changed hands frequently many bloody battles waged nearby including great victory over english forces at stirling bridge and robert the decisive defeat of edward ii at bannockburn ▫ robert the bruce had the defences destroyed to prevent it falling into enemy hands again it was not substantially rebuilt until when the english recaptured it the castle finally fell back into scottish hands in ▫ until the union of the crowns in almost every scottish monarch had either lived in the castle or been crowned or died here as such many grand celebrations took place at stirling from the coronation of mary queen of scots to the christening of her son and future king james vi and i ▫ today it remains a great symbol of scottish independence and national pride ▫ image by bryanmillarwalker
orig_caption:
Stirling Castle was first mentioned around 1100 and is considered as one of the most historically important sites in Scotland.
▫️
Throughout the Wars of Independence with England (1296–1356), Stirling was hotly fought over and changed hands frequently. Many bloody battles waged nearby, including Wallace’s great victory over English forces at Stirling Bridge (1297) and Robert the Bruce’s decisive defeat of Edward II at Bannockburn (1314).
▫️
Robert the Bruce had the castle’s defences destroyed to prevent it falling into enemy hands again. It was not substantially rebuilt until 1336, when the English recaptured it. The castle finally fell back into Scottish hands in 1342.
▫️
Until the Union of the Crowns in 1603, almost every Scottish monarch had either lived in the castle, or been crowned or died here. As such many grand celebrations took place at Stirling, from the coronation of Mary Queen of Scots to the christening of her son and future King James VI and I.
▫️
Today it remains a great symbol of Scottish independence and national pride.
▫️
Image by @bryanmillarwalker ———————————————————

Corporal Walter Norman Ellis, Service N°1917 27th Battalion and the 5th Machine Gun Battalion, 1st Australian Imperial Force, Summer 1915.
Walter Norman Ellis was born at Goodwood, South Australia on November 1892. He enlisted at Keswick 17 May 1915 and served with the 27th Infantry Battalion at Mudros, Ismailia and France. He was wounded in action in France on November 1917 and returned to Australia in 1919.

Inspired by the epic landscapes and colours of Wilson’s Promontory. This one was definitely sub consciously derived from the experiences I had camping out there. I love the idea that the mountains and a butterfly represent two opposite ends of the spectrum in a scale of time. Both are alive, and moving and evolving. To a human eye, one is fluttering at a speed that is so fast it becomes blurred, and one is moving so slow it appears completely still. Despite this, they’re essentially one in the same. -

caption: glowing warmly against the dark backdrop of the universe this irregular galaxy seen by our hubble space telescope nasahubble contains bright pockets of star formation located approximately million light years away host to a particularly interesting exploded star also known as a supernova in november year old caroline moore from new york discovered this supernova which made her the youngest person at the time to have discovered one follow up observations by professional astronomers showed that it was peculiarly interesting in many different ways first its host galaxy rarely produces supernovae it is also one of the faintest supernovae ever observed and after the explosion it expanded very slowly suggesting that the explosion did not release copious amounts of energy as usually expected astronomers have now classified it as a subclass of a type ia supernova which is the explosion of a white dwarf that hungrily accretes matter from a companion star it may have may have been the result of a partially failed supernova explaining why the explosion failed to decimate the whole star credit esahubble nasa
orig_caption:
Glowing warmly against the dark backdrop of the universe, this irregular galaxy seen by our Hubble Space Telescope (@NASAHubble) contains bright pockets of star formation. Located approximately 70 million light-years away, it’s host to a particularly interesting exploded star, also known as a supernova.

In November 2008, 14-year-old Caroline Moore from New York discovered this supernova, which made her the youngest person at the time to have discovered one. Follow-up observations by professional astronomers showed that it was peculiarly interesting in many different ways. 
First, its host galaxy rarely produces supernovae. It is also one of the faintest supernovae ever observed and after the explosion it expanded very slowly, suggesting that the explosion did not release copious amounts of energy as usually expected. Astronomers have now classified it as a subclass of a Type Ia supernova, which is the explosion of a white dwarf that hungrily accretes matter from a companion star. It may have may have been the result of a partially failed supernova, explaining why the explosion failed to decimate the whole star.

Credit: ESA/Hubble & NASA

caption: acquired on april this image from our mars reconnaissance orbiter shows aram chaos a kilometer diameter ancient impact crater that lies within in the southern highlands of mars the chiseled light toned layers composed largely of the iron oxide hematite and water altered silicates indicate that this crater once held a lake yet another nod to the red rich geologic past image credit nasajpl caltechuniv of arizona
orig_caption:
Acquired on April 1, this image from our Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter shows Aram Chaos, a 280 kilometer-diameter ancient impact crater that lies within in the Southern Highlands of Mars. The chiseled light-toned layers, composed largely of the iron-oxide hematite and water-altered silicates, indicate that this crater once held a lake. Yet another nod to the Red Planet’s rich geologic past. 
Image Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/Univ. of Arizona

orig_caption:
I was listening to a podcast this morning..
.
The msg I’m getting is —> What are you sacrificing because you’re too comfortable?
.
If you’re not willing to take a step back or sacrifice (discomfort), you’re not finding your true potential💫
.
What’s a step back or discomfort 🤷🏻‍♀️
- Status
- People’s opinions of you
- Others expectations
- Being a beginner
- Looking silly
- Starting from the bottom
- Earning less now for more later 
It could go on right ?!
.
I’m sure it’s different for all.
I know for me personally, I was willing to leave a good paying job in order to build true wealth and follow that ‘excitement’.
.
I had r’ships go balls up because what I was doing wasn’t ‘liked’ or more so, understood at the time.
.
I’ve gotten more ‘No’s’ or rejection by the age of 30 than most people do in their LIFEtime and that has been a choice of discomfort I’m SO okay with.
.
Saying ‘YES’ to things that make my stomach turn but trusting myself enough to know I’ll be okay.
.
So babes, always ask yourself—> When was the last time you sacrificed ‘comfort’ (without whinging about it) to find true potential? .
True potential is where we build + find our best selves. .
And if you’re not excited by the person you will get to be and meet in 5yrs, 10yrs ++, from the decisions + discomfort you’re choosing now...(firstly, WTF! 💁🏻‍♀️ do you know how incredible she will be?!)
....maybe look at what you’re sacrificing because you’re too damn comfortable. .
You’re always sacrificing something. You just get to choose what. .
I know I have. 
And these next 6mths, I feel HUGE discomfort happening...therefore huge potential available. Fck YES ! .
P.S Photo is totally irrelevant but helloooo views ! 😍

orig_caption:
Built by the 4th Earl of Caithness in the late 16th Century, the then Barrogill Castle latterly became the seat of the Sinclair family and played host to many notable guests, including a visit from Edward VII and Queen Alexandra. The castle remained in the Sinclair family until 1889.
▫️
Subsequently the castle was passed on to P.G. Heathcote and then to Captain Imbert-Terry, after which the castle fell in to a poor state of repair.
▫️
In 1952, while mourning the death of her husband, King George VI, Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother came across the castle and after learning of its doomed fate, sought to save it. She did exactly that, spending every August and October at the castle from 1955 to 2001. On her last visit she was 101 years old.
▫️
Located in the county of Caithness, the Castle of Mey is the most northernly castle on the British Mainland.
▫️
Image by @benjaminpuckey ———————————————————

caption: well i grew up listening to tim mcgraw because it was my brothers favorite artist he was always in the passenger seat because he was older and the only boy so hed get to control the fm stations he would turn on and sing off key to tim mcgraw all the time hed say you know tim mcgraw has a really hard voice to sing so you have to sing really high or really low then hed belt out im going to live where the green grass grows but his favorite was always bbq stain on my white t shirtttt as always off key so we grew up listening to country music my parents preferred it over the spice girls nsync and the backstreet boys my partner didnt grow up with country music so it took him by surprise when i told him that was my favorite genre i did grow up in orange county after all in our time together ive really hated the new direction country music has moved in so was thrilled when he surprised me with tim mcgraw tickets especially because they both sing their classic songs in concert still the crowd was so pleasant and kind everyone was well mannered and open hearted more on the blog
orig_caption:
Well, I grew up listening to Tim Mcgraw because it was my brother's favorite artist.  He was always in the passenger seat (because he was older and the only boy) so he'd get to control the FM stations.  He would turn on 93.9 and sing off-key to Tim Mcgraw, all the time.  He'd say, "You know, Tim Mcgraw has a really hard voice to sing so you have to sing really high or really low." Then he'd belt out, "I'm going to live where the green grass grows." But his favorite was always, "bbq stain on my white t-shirtttt." As always, off-key.
-
 So we grew up listening to country music.  My parents preferred it over the spice girls, nsync, and the backstreet boys.
- My partner didn't grow up with country music, so it took him by surprise when I told him that was my favorite genre.  I did grow up in Orange County after all.  In our time together, I've really hated the new direction country music has moved in ... so was thrilled when he surprised me with Tim Mcgraw tickets! Especially because they both sing their classic songs in concert, still.  The crowd was so pleasant and kind.  Everyone was well-mannered and open-hearted. •

caption: buchanan castle is the site of an earlier castle historically owned by clan buchanan since the th century however following the death of the last laird of buchanan in the castle and estate were bought by the rd duke of montrose of the graham family ▫ unfortunately the original castle burned down in the current building was built by the th duke of montrose in and became the official seat of clan graham ▫ the castle was sold in and was used as a hospital during the second world war one of the patients there was rudolf hess the roof was removed after the war and the building fell into disrepair ▫ image by wilbo
orig_caption:
Buchanan Castle is the site of an earlier castle, historically owned by Clan Buchanan since the 13th century. However, following the death of the last Laird of Buchanan in 1681, the castle and estate were bought by the 3rd Duke of Montrose (of the Graham family).
▫️
Unfortunately, the original castle burned down in 1842. The current building was built by the 4th Duke of Montrose in 1854 and became the official seat of Clan Graham.
▫️
The castle was sold in 1925, and was used as a hospital during the Second World War - one of the patients there was Rudolf Hess. The roof was removed after the war, and the building fell into disrepair.
▫️
Image by @wilbo2222 ———————————————————-

caption: the snowy egret egretta thula is a beautiful sight an adult egret is distinguished by its dark slender beak long black legs and yellow feet perhaps its most notable feature the showy plumes or feathers that grow on its head and back in fact great demand for these spectacular plumeswhich were used to make fashionable ladies hatsalmost led to the birds extinction by the early s the migratory bird treaty act signed into law in saved this species photo david sutton
orig_caption:
The Snowy Egret (Egretta thula) is a beautiful sight. An adult egret is distinguished by its dark slender beak, long black legs, and yellow feet. Perhaps its most notable feature? The showy plumes, or feathers, that grow on its head and back. In fact, great demand for these spectacular plumes—which were used to make fashionable ladies’ hats—almost led to the birds' extinction by the early 1900s. The Migratory Bird Treaty Act, signed into law in 1918, saved this species.
Photo: David Sutton

orig_caption:
Tolquhon Castle was built during the early fifteenth century by Sir Henry Preston. The main feature was a Tower House which was surrounded by a barmkin (curtain wall) enclosing the ancillary buildings such as brewhouse, bakehouse and stables. Sir Henry died in 1420 without leaving a male heir and his estates were subsequently divided between his daughters.
▫️
Tolquhon Castle passed through his second daughter, Marjorie, to her husband, Sir John Forbes. It would remain with his family for almost 300 years.
▫️
The castle was rebuilt by William Forbes between 1584 and 1589. After his death Tolquhon Castle passed to his son, William. Further upgrades to the castle were planned but were never enacted nor were any additional modifications made by any of his successors although the surrounding gardens were re-landscaped in the late seventeenth century.
▫️
It was during this period that the Forbes rose in prominence under the Stewart monarchs. Alexander Forbes had saved the life of Charles II during the Battle of Worcester (1651) and, after the Restoration of the monarchy, was knighted. The family remained loyal to the Stewarts even after the Glorious Revolution and accordingly the then owner, William Forbes, supported the 1715 Jacobite Rebellion. Parliament declared his estates forfeit in 1716 but he refused to vacate and had to be forcibly evicted in September 1718.
▫️
Tolquhon Castle ceased to be a high status residence at this time and was eventually purchased by the Earl of Aberdeen to use as a farm house. It continued in this role until the early nineteenth century and thereafter was allowed to drift into ruin.
▫️

orig_caption:
Many people ask questions like "When am I going to get my breakthrough?" Many people are obsessed with the idea of a breakthrough or favor or provision. I believe that one of the greatest truths is that life is not about you…
.
When we understand that, we will experience a huge shift or "breakthrough" in life. When we get the focus off of ourselves and onto others, serving the Lord and helping His people, all of a sudden things look a lot brighter.
.
One of the biggest tricks of the devil is to get you so focused on yourself that you can't even see anyone else. Then, if you do see them, you are more likely to compare, criticize or judge.
.
Let's remember today that we didn't wake up to be served by others, but to serve and to be a light. I pray that this can serve as a "breakthrough" as we get out of ourselves and put the focus on serving the Lord and helping others. 🙏

orig_caption:
Kirkwall is the capital of Orkney. For centuries it was the capital of the Norse-held Nordreyjar – the Northern Isles. But that ended in 1469 when Christian I of Norway failed to pay the dowry promised to his son-in-law, James III of Scotland; James called in the debt by assuming sovereignty of Orkney and Shetland.
▫️
Kirkwall was graced by three fortified medieval residences. Two of these were the Bishop’s Palace and Earl’s Palace.
▫️
The Bishop’s Palace was built around the same time as St Magnus’s Cathedral, in the early 12th century. The builder may well have been Bishop William ‘the Old’ (d.1168), crusader and friend of Earl Rognvald, St Magnus’s nephew and patron of the new cathedral.
▫️
Following defeat at the Battle of Largs in 1263, King Hakon IV of Norway died within the walls of the Bishop’s Palace. By 1320, the palace had been reduced to ruins through neglect.
▫️
The building returned to prominence in 1540, when King James V of Scotland arrived in Kirkwall and garrisoned his troops in Kirkwall Castle and the Bishop's Palace.
▫️
Soon after, Bishop Robert Reid, the founder of Edinburgh University and the last and greatest of Orkney's medieval Bishops, began an extensive programme of restoration and reconstruction.
▫️
In the early 1600s, the Bishop's Palace was incorporated into a refined Renaissance palace commissioned by Earl Patrick Stewart, one of Orkney's most notorious rulers.
▫️
Today the palace is open to the public and is administered by Historic Environment Scotland as a scheduled monument.
▫️

Summer is hardly over and I’m already seeing back-to-school ads in my local stores. I don’t know about you guys, but—when I was in school—I was most concerned with my classroom supplies, getting a new backpack, and what I was going to wear for the first week back to class. It’s funny how we spend so much time prepping for our education, but very little time preparing our spirits for what it takes to be a Christian on and off campus. Any place you go becomes and mission field for God when you are an ambassador for Christ. That doesn’t mean shouting scriptures at the top of your lungs when you walk down the hallway, but it does mean building up your faith and preparing yourself to be a witness in the midst of peer pressure, bullying, drama, and gossip. In my latest YouTube video, I talk about four ways to keep your walk with God strong on campus. Whether you’re in middle school, high school, or college (or know someone who is), click on the link in my bio to watch. Share with anyone you think could benefit from this information it as well. orig_caption:
Today we started a new chapter of our lives together. After a lot of talk about the future, (planning a wedding gets you talking about a lot of things that aren’t the wedding 😂), we decided it was time to make a move. Literally. I’ve taken a job doing travel Speech Therapy, so that Bean and I can explore the country in a new state and city every 3 months and live a life that is more in tune with ourselves and the planet! This is a back up plan, as I really just wanted to live in a van and travel. But this seems more responsible... for now 😊😉We sold our 2000 era Honda Accords and traded up for a gently used Toyota RAV4  whom we’ve Named Simon🚙. We moved our big furniture into storage and kept only what Simon could hold. Including our awesome golden doodle, Hazel Mae. We’re excited to explore  as many US national parks and forests as possible in these next few months.... We are definitely sad to leave Columbus— it’s been our home for 2+ years, and Home to so many wonderful people we are lucky to call our friends. There is only one place that could have made us leave so quickly, and that is Lake Tahoe for our first stop! This page will be used to share our adventures on the road and off. Follow along if want to see what we’re up to, and if you have any recommendations for our next place, Let me know!!!! #beanandme #hazelscomingtoo

And also, COME VISIT!!!

caption: midhope castle is a th century tower house and belonged to the drummonds of midhope who were in possession during part of the th and th centuries ▫ alexander drummond of midhope remodelled the tower in and his initials with those of his wife marjorie bruce are on a former lintel now above a gateway ▫ the property passed to the livingstones in and the intials of george livingstone rd earl of linlithgow are also on a lintel before going on to the hopes in ▫ midhope was used to house farm workers after the building of nearby hopetoun house and in people lived here but it was later abandoned and is now semi derelict ▫ more recently midhope castle features as lallybroch in the tv series outlander ▫ image by spectacularscotland
orig_caption:
Midhope Castle is a 16th-century tower house and belonged to the Drummonds of Midhope, who were in possession during part of the 16th and 17th centuries.
▫️
Alexander Drummond of Midhope remodelled the tower in 1587 and his initials, with those of his wife Marjorie Bruce are on a former lintel now above a gateway.
▫️
The property passed to the Livingstones in 1664, and the intials of George Livingstone, 3rd Earl of Linlithgow are also on a lintel, before going on to the Hopes in 1678.
▫️
Midhope was used to house farm workers after the building of nearby Hopetoun House, and in 1851, 53 people lived here, but it was later abandoned and is now semi-derelict.
▫️
More recently, Midhope Castle features as ‘Lallybroch’ in the TV series ‘Outlander’.
▫️

caption: keiss castle was built in the late th century by george sinclair fifth earl of caithness it stands at the northern end of sinclair bay and was one of three fortifications that controlled this territory the others were ackergill castle and girnigoe castle ▫ the first record of the castle dates from when george defied king james vi i of england in response the king dispatched sir robert gordon to raid caithness and although the rebellious earl provisioned his castles for a siege he withdrew to orkney all three castles surrendered without a fight to sir robert but were eventually returned to the earls son george lord berriedale ▫ in the castle passed to george sinclair sixth earl of caithness he built thurso castle which he used as his main residence with keiss being allowed to decay this was only exacerbated when the sinclairs found themselves embroiled in a bitter dispute over land and title with the campbells of glenorchy first the courts then the king supported the latter prompting sinclair to mount a protracted guerrilla campaign against his rivals ▫ it was only intervention by james duke of york later james vii and ii that the sinclairs were restored by this time keiss castle itself was ruinous although some repairs were made over the following decades for some form of dwelling ▫ image by glebovaanastasia
orig_caption:
Keiss Castle was built in the late 16th century by George Sinclair, Fifth Earl of Caithness. It stands at the northern end of Sinclair Bay and was one of three fortifications that controlled this territory (the others were Ackergill Castle and Girnigoe Castle).
▫️
The first record of the castle dates from 1623 when George defied King James VI (I of England). In response the King dispatched Sir Robert Gordon to raid Caithness and, although the rebellious Earl provisioned his castles for a siege, he withdrew to Orkney. All three castles surrendered without a fight to Sir Robert but were eventually returned to the Earl's son - George, Lord Berriedale.
▫️
In 1643 the castle passed to George Sinclair, Sixth Earl of Caithness. He built Thurso Castle which he used as his main residence with Keiss being allowed to decay. This was only exacerbated when the Sinclairs found themselves embroiled in a bitter dispute over land and title with the Campbells of Glenorchy. First the courts, then the King supported the latter, prompting Sinclair to mount a protracted guerrilla campaign against his rivals.
▫️
It was only intervention by James, Duke of York (later James VII and II) that the Sinclairs were restored. By this time, Keiss Castle itself was ruinous although some repairs were made over the following decades for some form of dwelling.
▫️

caption: 🔷 progressive overload 🔶 🔘 when it comes to training there are so many ways to progressively overload the body and introduce new stimulus however too many people forget how to structure their training so that they can continue to see results 🔘 say on monday you deadlift lbs for sets of reps and then on wednesday you deadlift lbs for sets of reps you basically increased the weight and added a new stimulus 🔘 now say you are in the gym on friday and seem to find any more plates to add to the bar you can then deadlift lbs for sets of reps you basically increased the amount of reps you did and added a new stimulus this is basically the same for adding sets to a certain exercise just add an extra set of however many reps you were doing on any given exercise 🔘 lets say that now you been months and you are bored with the same workout been doing and you feel like the deadlift has become way too easy you can use more difficult variations of it and what i mean by that is to further push your deadlift gains try using a more difficult exercise like a single leg deadlift decrease the load you have on the bar and start working on the unilateral pattern although you would have to sacrifice how much weight you use in the long run you would eventually work your way up to that weight but on a harder variation and when you return to your standard deadlift you will have made tons of gains 🔘 progressive overload works for all exercises if you prepping for a physique competition powerlifting meet strongman event nfl combine etc then you should never complain about why you absolutely need a squat rack bench press deadlift platform or why you absolutely need to only add weight to the bar and just do more reps and sets 🔘 where there is a will there is a way
orig_caption:
🔷PROGRESSIVE OVERLOAD 🔶
-
🔘When it comes to training there are so many ways to progressively overload the body and introduce new stimulus however too many people forget how to structure their training so that they can continue to see results.
-
🔘Let’s say on Monday you deadlift 225lbs for 4 sets of 6 reps and then on Wednesday you deadlift 230lbs for 4 sets of 6 reps, you basically increased the weight and added a new stimulus.
-
🔘Now let’s say you are in the gym on Friday and can’t seem to find any more plates to add to the bar, you can then deadlift 230lbs for 4 sets of 7 reps, you basically increased the amount of reps you did and added a new stimulus. This is basically the same for adding sets to a certain exercise: just add an extra set of however many reps you were doing on any given exercise.
-
🔘Lets say that now you it’s been 2 months and you are bored with the same workout you’ve been doing and you feel like the deadlift has become way too easy, you can use more difficult variations of it and what I mean by that is to further push your deadlift gains try using a more difficult exercise like a single leg deadlift. Decrease the load you have on the bar and start working on the unilateral pattern. Although you would have to sacrifice how much weight you use, in the long run you would eventually work your way up to that weight but on a harder variation and when you return to your standard deadlift you will have made tons of gains.
-
🔘progressive overload works for all exercises, if you aren’t prepping for a physique competition, powerlifting meet, strongman event, NFL combine, etc... then you should never complain about why you absolutely need a squat rack, bench press, deadlift platform, or why you absolutely need to only add weight to the bar and can’t just do more reps and sets. -
🔘where there is a will there is a way

orig_caption: In India, summer heat may soon be unbearable — literally. Extreme heat can kill, as it did by the dozens in Pakistan in May. But as many of South Asia’s already-scorching cities get even hotter, scientists and economists are warning of a quieter, more far-reaching danger: Extreme #heat is devastating the health and livelihoods of tens of millions more. Heat is already making the poor poorer and sicker. There’s the Kolkata street vendor who squats from fatigue and nausea, the woman who passes out from heatstroke while selling water to tourists in Delhi and the people in emergency rooms with fever and headaches. A recent analysis of climate trends in several of South Asia’s biggest cities found that if current warming trends continued, by the end of the century, wet bulb temperatures — a measure of heat and humidity that can indicate the point when the body can no longer cool itself — would be so high that people directly exposed for 6 hours or more wouldn’t survive. In Delhi, @khandelwal_saumya photographed Kripa Devi, a water and lemonade vendor who struggles with the heat and says she regularly falls ill. The city’s heat index has risen sharply — by 0.6 degrees Celsius in summer and 0.55 degrees during monsoons per decade between 1951 and 2010, according to one analysis. Visit the link in our profile to read more.

orig_caption: Manhattanhenge comes twice a year—and tonight’s the second and last chance to see it in 2018! It occurs when the setting Sun aligns precisely with the Manhattan street grid to create a radiant glow of light across the city’s brick-and-steel canyons. The phenomenon simultaneously illuminates both the north and south sides of cross streets on the grid. For best effect, position yourself as far east in Manhattan as possible. But ensure that when you look west across the avenues, you can still see New Jersey. Clear cross streets include 14th, 23rd, 34th, 42nd, and 57th. 📸 M. Shanley/©AMNH

caption: an aurora is an incredible natural phenomenon this spectral display is created when electrically charged particles from the sun enter the atmosphere the changes in color are from the types of gas particle colliding according to the northern lights centre the most common auroral color a pale yellowish green is produced by oxygen molecules located about miles above the earth rare all red auroras are produced by high altitude oxygen at heights of up to miles nitrogen produces blue or purplish red aurora the lights can be found above the magnetic poles in the northern hemisphere where is it called aurora borealis and in the southern hemisphere where it is aurora australis
orig_caption: An Aurora is an incredible natural phenomenon. This spectral display is created when electrically-charged particles from the sun enter the Earth’s atmosphere. The changes in color are from the types of gas-particle colliding. According to the Northern Lights Centre, “The most common auroral color, a pale yellowish-green, is produced by oxygen molecules located about 60 miles above the earth. Rare, all-red auroras are produced by high-altitude oxygen, at heights of up to 200 miles. Nitrogen produces blue or purplish-red aurora.” The lights can be found above the magnetic poles in the Northern Hemisphere, where is it called ‘Aurora borealis’ and in the Southern Hemisphere, where it is ‘Aurora australis.’ #amazing #auroraborealis #northernlights #science

orig_caption:
Nine European Sovereigns at Windsor for the funeral of King Edward VII in May of 1910, four years before the war began. Standing, from left to right: King Haakon VII of Norway, Tsar Ferdinand of Bulgaria, King Manuel II of Portugal, Kaiser Wilhelm II of the German Empire, King George I of Greece and King Albert I of Belgium. Seated, from left to right: King Alfonso XIII of Spain, King-Emperor George V of the United Kingdom and King Frederick VIII of Denmark. Within the next decade, Kaiser Wilhelm II and Tsar Ferdinand's empires would engage in bloody warfare with the nations led by King Albert I and King George V. The war was also a family affair, as Kaiser Wilhelm II was a first cousin to King George V, and an uncle to King Albert I. Of the remaining monarchs pictured, over the next decade one would be assassinated (Greece), three would keep their nations neutral (Norway, Spain, and Denmark), and two would be forced out of power by revolutions.

orig_caption:
Built on a rock in an idyllic loch side setting on the Isle of Skye, Dunvegan is the oldest continuously inhabited castle in Scotland and has been the ancestral home of the Chiefs of Clan MacLeod for 800 years.
▫️
On display within Dunvegan are many fine oil paintings and clan treasures, the most famous of which is the Fairy Flag. Legend has it that this sacred banner has miraculous powers and when unfurled in battle, the clan MacLeod would invariably defeat their enemies.
▫️
Another of the castle's great treasures is the Dunvegan Cup, a unique 'mazer' dating back to the Middle Ages. It was gifted by the O'Neils of Ulster as a token of thanks to one of our most celebrated Chiefs, Sir Rory Mor, for his support of their cause against the marauding forces of Queen Elizabeth I of England in 1595.
▫️
There is also a small collection of Bonnie Prince Charlie related items on display including: one of the Prince’s waistcoats, a Jacobite amen glass, and a lock of the Prince’s hair.
▫️
Image by @pickettkev ———————————————————

orig_caption: As many of you may know, missing the “bull’s eye” in the sport of archery is actually called a “sin”. It’s a misfire. Understandably enough, there are countless ways to miss. To come up short. Inadequacy. To overshoot. Overzealous. Hubris. Clouded by ambition. Or you could be just slightly off. A seemingly insignificant sin yet still dishonoring. Regardless, sin literally means missing the mark. So often, we miss the mark. This is such a disheartening truth that compels us to find compensation. This “compensation” also takes on many forms, most of which are other sins ironically enough. But the only remedy for our inability to hit the mark is Jesus Christ. Through his bloodshed, we have forgiveness. This changes everything. This integrates a spirit of redemption. We can take refuge in him (Psalm 46:1). He renews our strength (Isaiah 40:31). He cleanses is from all unrighteousness (1 John 1:9). So, as you and I both repetitively miss the mark, let us turn to Jesus not as a last resort but as our first option. #summer #camp #archery #sports #instapic #fitspo #fit #sun #instagood #tb #like #followme #ministry #la #passion #joy #love #handlelife #summerbody #2018 #redemption #church #Jesus #believer #scripture #blessed #grateful #praiseGod

caption: the macdonalds or clan donald were lords of the isles and their kingdom covered a vast area of western scotland the clan played a pivotal role in the history of the highlands from clan warfare to the jacobite rising and the eventual breakdown of the traditional clan system ▫ clan donald came to skye in the th century and held castles at duntulm knock dunscaith and armadale from around the clan chiefs began to stay at armadale and the mansion house later became a dower house for the widows of clan chiefs ▫ perhaps the most famous visitor to the old mansion house at armadale was flora macdonald known for her role in helping bonnie prince charlie escape capture she was married at armadale castle in later visitors included samuel johnson and his biographer james boswell who visited in as part of their famous journey through the western isles ▫ a new mansion house was built in and extended in to form the present armadale castle unfortunately the castle was gutted by fire in most of the mansion was destroyed ▫ the central section was rebuilt leaving the remainder a picturesque ruin the macdonald family moved to a smaller house on the estate in and today only the ruins of armadale castle remain ▫ image by dianalou
orig_caption:
The MacDonalds, or Clan Donald, were Lords of the Isles, and their kingdom covered a vast area of western Scotland. The Clan played a pivotal role in the history of the Highlands, from clan warfare to the Jacobite Rising, and the eventual breakdown of the traditional clan system.
▫️
Clan Donald came to Skye in the 15th century and held castles at Duntulm, Knock, Dunscaith, and Armadale. From around 1650 the clan chiefs began to stay at Armadale, and the mansion house later became a dower house for the widows of clan chiefs.
▫️
Perhaps the most famous visitor to the old mansion house at Armadale was Flora MacDonald, known for her role in helping Bonnie Prince Charlie escape capture. She was married at Armadale Castle in 1750. Later visitors included Samuel Johnson and his biographer, James Boswell, who visited in 1773 as part of their famous journey through the Western Isles.
▫️
A new mansion house was built in 1790 and extended in 1815 to form the present Armadale Castle. Unfortunately, the castle was gutted by fire in 1855. Most of the mansion was destroyed.
▫️
The central section was rebuilt, leaving the remainder a picturesque ruin. The MacDonald family moved to a smaller house on the estate in 1925, and today only the ruins of Armadale Castle remain.
▫️
Image by @dianalou9 ———————————————————
